We start by writing $x-18$ inside the parentheses.  We want to get the solution for $x$.  Hence, we isolate $x-18$ first. $$\log_5(x-18)=2$$ From the problem, we must isolate $x-18$, so we subtract $2$. $$\log_5(x-18)=2$$ $$\log_5(x-18)-2=0$$ Now we would try to get rid of the $\log_5$ still on the left side of the equation. But if we multiply both sides of the equation by $5$, the $\log$ disappears. $$5(\log_5(x-18)-2)=5(0)$$ So now let’s multiply both sides of the equation: 
$$5\log_5(x-18)-5(2)=5(0)$$
 $$\boxed{\Large{5}}\log_5(x-18)-\boxed{\Large{10}}=\boxed{\Large{0}}$$ ($5(2)=10$).  We bring $5$ to the front of the equation by factoring this equation. 
$$\boxed{\Large{5}}\log_5(x-18)=\boxed{\Large{10}}$$ Now to undo the $\log_5(x-18)$, we put the reciprocal of the left side of the equation as the new right side and vice versa.  This way, the $\log_5(x-18)$ on the left side practically reveals its value right side.
$$5=10/(x-18)$$
Here, we are interested in finding the value of $x$.  So we multiply each side of the equation by $(x-18)$ to linearize the equation. 
$$5(x-18)=10$$ Multiply each side by the reciprocal of $5$ which is $1/5$.
$$(x-18)=2$$  Now we have $x$ which we want to find.  This step gives the value $x$.  We substitute the value $x=2+18$, which gives $x=20$.
